SUBJECTIVE: Patient reports his joints, back and knees are hurting more. He states his joints became swollen at the end of Jan. and had to stop his home exercise program since then. Patient also reports he has not attempted to start a pool exercise program. Patient reports he is taking Methotrexate, 25 mg, 2x/day, and tylenol with codeine 2x/day. Patient reports he will follow up with his rheumatologist in May. Patient reports he tries attempts house work when he is not having major pain.
Patient Goals: 0-10 Scale (0=no problem 10=unable to perform) -Going down steps 8 -Squatting 10 -Sitting 15 min. 9 Pain: 7/10
(3/5/14) -Going down steps 4 -Squatting 5 -Sitting 15 min. 6 Pain: 1/10
(10/3/14) -Going down steps 8 -Squatting 9 -Sitting 15 min. 7 Pain: 6/10
OBJECTIVE:
-MRI of lumbar spine shows severe lumbar facet arthritis L4-5
Observation: -Weak core musculature -Patient with weakness to bilateral hip and quad musculature -Patient with tightness to bilateral quad musculature - Patient able to ambulate with assistive device
Shoulder active range of motion: -Right: flexion 120 extension 30 abduction 120 external rotation 60 internal rotation L1 -Left: flexion 110 extension 40 abduction 115 external rotation 50 internal rotation L1
Shoulder strength: 4-/5 to all planes bilaterally
Palpation: -Pain to bilateral IT band -Pain around L patella -Crepitus around L patella -Pain to supraspinatus
Sensation: -intact
Outcome Measures: Mobility: -Scoring: 1-4; 1=Totally Dependent 2=Requires assistance of a person (with or without appliance), 3=Requires appliances, orthosis or prosthesis for independence, 4=Totally independent (indoors/outdoors), -Ambulation: 2 -Transfers: 1 -Wheelchair: 1 -Total: 4/12
Education Provided: -Standing straight leg raise flexion abduction extension, supine pelvic tilt, supine lumbar rotations, supine bridging, long arc quads, standing calf raises, prone quadricep stretching (patient reeducated on how to perform her home exercise program -Upper trap and pec. minor stretching, shoulder range of motion, scapular retraction, and shoulder shrugs added to home exercise program
Patient/Caregiver demonstrated understanding of the education: Yes
ASSESSMENT: Patient presents with acute joint pain related to his RA. Patient would benefit from physical therapy for wrist range of motion, shoulder shrugs, and stretching of pec. minor and levator scapulae. Patient is unable to performe hep. Patient should continue his home exercise program with assistance when his pain loweres and if he does not have some improvement in the next month, he should ask his local PCP to refer him to local physical therapy services.
Need for Physical Therapy services: Yes, 3 more visits
Prognosis with Physical Therapy: Fair to Good
Need for other Rehabilitation Medicine Department services: Yes ;
Need for rehabilitation services post discharge: Yes ;
PLAN: Follow up 1/20/15 due to patients schedule and distance from clinic. Patient to perform the above home exercise program daily. Recheck patients progress at the next visit. If improvement is seen then home exercise program should be adjusted. Patient to have translator present at next visit.
Goals: (3/13/15) -Going down steps 4 -Squatting 6 -Sitting 15 min. 2
Pain: 5/10
Patient/Caregiver participated in and agreed to the development of the plan of care and treatment goals.
Patient/Caregiver to contact physical therapist with any questions or concerns regarding physical therapy assessment and treatment.
